00:52:41.557 --> 00:52:43.140
If it's a home equity
line, if there's

00:52:43.140 --> 00:52:46.750
a variable versus fixed, what
are you looking for as far as--

00:52:46.750 --> 00:52:49.200
you know, you mentioned
7% or 8% return--

00:52:49.200 --> 00:52:50.413
kind of that gap?

00:52:50.413 --> 00:52:52.080
What's that spread
that you kind of look

00:52:52.080 --> 00:52:55.530
for to decide whether or not
it's meaningful to actually

00:52:55.530 --> 00:52:56.860
pull money out of investments?

00:52:56.860 --> 00:52:58.930
PAULA PANT: Oh, that's
an excellent question.

00:52:58.930 --> 00:53:02.310
So the concept of, if you
have a significant amount

00:53:02.310 --> 00:53:05.790
of home equity in your
personal residence,

00:53:05.790 --> 00:53:08.605
pulling that home equity
out to invest-- now

00:53:08.605 --> 00:53:10.230
first thing I'll say
is a lot of people

00:53:10.230 --> 00:53:13.033
have a knee-jerk reaction
to this where they think,

00:53:13.033 --> 00:53:13.950
oh, no, don't do that.

00:53:13.950 --> 00:53:14.908
That's not a good idea.

00:53:14.908 --> 00:53:16.710
But if you think
about it logically,

00:53:16.710 --> 00:53:18.825
right, what is the
difference between--

00:53:22.130 --> 00:53:25.190
what is the difference
between taking money

00:53:25.190 --> 00:53:28.550
that you would otherwise use
to make accelerated mortgage

00:53:28.550 --> 00:53:32.768
payments and using that for an
alternate purpose versus having

00:53:32.768 --> 00:53:34.310
a good amount of
home equity and then

00:53:34.310 --> 00:53:38.270
borrowing against it for
same said alternate purpose.

00:53:38.270 --> 00:53:39.160
Right?

00:53:39.160 --> 00:53:43.670
At a functional level, those
are exactly the same actions.

00:53:43.670 --> 00:53:46.640
But a lot of people will say--

00:53:46.640 --> 00:53:50.918
you know, person A will say
I'm not making any accelerated

00:53:50.918 --> 00:53:53.210
payments towards my mortgage
because I would rather put

00:53:53.210 --> 00:53:56.030
that money into investment x.

00:53:56.030 --> 00:54:01.070
And person B would say I am
making accelerated payments

00:54:01.070 --> 00:54:02.390
towards my mortgage.

00:54:02.390 --> 00:54:05.178
And now, look, I've got
all of this home equity.

00:54:05.178 --> 00:54:07.220
I'm going to borrow against
it and put that money

00:54:07.220 --> 00:54:08.250
towards investment x.

00:54:08.250 --> 00:54:08.750
Right?

00:54:08.750 --> 00:54:10.118
Like it's the same thing.

00:54:10.118 --> 00:54:11.660
So the first thing
I'll say-- and I'm

00:54:11.660 --> 00:54:14.077
saying this for the sake of
everyone who's listening-- is,

00:54:14.077 --> 00:54:16.220
you know, don't have
that knee-jerk reaction

00:54:16.220 --> 00:54:18.440
against borrowing
against the equity

00:54:18.440 --> 00:54:24.380
in your personal residence
because, in many ways,

00:54:24.380 --> 00:54:29.340
many of us are already doing
it through opportunity cost.

00:54:29.340 --> 00:54:31.250
So then to answer your
specific question,

00:54:31.250 --> 00:54:34.010
how would I think through
whether or not to do it

00:54:34.010 --> 00:54:35.510
for a given investment?

00:54:38.180 --> 00:54:41.270
The first thing that
I would ask is not

00:54:41.270 --> 00:54:43.050
the potential return
on that investment,

00:54:43.050 --> 00:54:45.960
but I would ask what
is the risk of ruin.

00:54:45.960 --> 00:54:46.460
Right?

00:54:46.460 --> 00:54:50.600
What are the chances that
that money that you withdraw

00:54:50.600 --> 00:54:52.760
could go down to zero?

00:54:52.760 --> 00:54:56.930
On something like a
broad market index fund

00:54:56.930 --> 00:55:02.160
or a rental property, the
chances of that falling,

00:55:02.160 --> 00:55:03.560
sure, that's there.

00:55:03.560 --> 00:55:07.730
But the chances of that
dropping by 50%, you know,

00:55:07.730 --> 00:55:12.620
or losing a very
significant amount of money

00:55:12.620 --> 00:55:18.265
is, historically speaking,
not that likely to happen.

00:55:18.265 --> 00:55:22.700
You know, so in that regard,
your downside is, at least

00:55:22.700 --> 00:55:24.950
historically speaking, limited.

00:55:24.950 --> 00:55:29.410
And to that extent,
that makes it

00:55:29.410 --> 00:55:32.950
safer than say taking
out that same HELOC

00:55:32.950 --> 00:55:36.725
and using it to start your own
business, which could go down

00:55:36.725 --> 00:55:37.225
to zero.

00:55:40.370 --> 00:55:42.080
So that's the way
that I would approach

00:55:42.080 --> 00:55:44.270
it is manage the downside.

00:55:44.270 --> 00:55:45.950
Manage the risk of ruin.

00:55:45.950 --> 00:55:51.630
Because so long as that money,
in a worst case scenario,

00:55:51.630 --> 00:55:54.770
so long as even if you
don't make any returns,

00:55:54.770 --> 00:55:57.205
if at the end of the
day, you break even,

00:55:57.205 --> 00:55:59.330
and then you're mad at
yourself because you've just

00:55:59.330 --> 00:56:02.480
paid a bunch of closing
costs, that's not

00:56:02.480 --> 00:56:04.300
going to be a deathbed regret.

